<paragraph id="A61A36A101546672FF12FF3CFE7F4686" blockId="10.[151,1437,153,791]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
Male specimens above listed have tegmina as long as or just longer than abdomen; they have been collected in the 
<typeStatus id="791E880301546672FF14FF18FF7046AA" box="[193,241,189,215]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="61A54D2201546672FEA7FF1BFE5146AA" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1870" box="[370,464,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphagidae" genus="Pagopedilum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis id="94D1EAB301546672FEA7FF1BFE5146AA" box="[370,464,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">P. brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, of which only the female nymph was known. Thus, this is the first record of the adult male and female of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EEBF652A01546672FF12FEA1FD8C456A" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" type="description">
<paragraph id="A61A36A101546672FF12FEA1FD424442" blockId="10.[151,1437,153,791]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="94D1EAB301546672FF12FEA1FE454762" bold="true" box="[199,452,260,287]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">Description of adults</emphasis>
. Male (Figs. 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, 32, 33, 34). Large and granulose, antennae missing. Fastigium of vertex above narrow, with angulate apex, in lateral view straight. Crest of pronotum thin, high and strongly curved in lateral view, not serrated in metazona, with shallow transverse sulci and three 
<emphasis id="94D1EAB301546672FB55FEE8FB66471A" box="[1152,1255,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">fenestrae</emphasis>
. Tegmina wide, not exceeding the end of abdomen and as long as ¾ of the hind femora, with regularly excurved anterior and nearly pointed apical margins, and with ca. 18-20 stridulatory veins. Hind femur moderately long, relatively stout; upper margin with short, acute teeth, lower margin shallowly serrated. Apical valves of penis stout, narrow, and covered with many small teeth. Posterior margin of epiphallus excurved, pseudolophi placed anteriorly with few teeth. General colouration brownish-grey; on side of pronotum on eye level there is a whitish stripe that continues straight on tegmina (Fig. 12). Second pair of wings vestigial.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A61A36A101546672FF12FDECFA0244FA" blockId="10.[151,1437,153,791]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
Female (Figs. 23, 24). Same characters of the male with the following differences. The pronotum crest is moderately high, 
<emphasis id="94D1EAB301546672FEFFFDC8FE1044FA" box="[298,401,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">fenestrae</emphasis>
are well visible. Abdominal tergites have a small spine on the posterior margin. Apterous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A61A36A101546672FF12FD37FD18448E" blockId="10.[151,1437,153,791]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName id="61A54D2201546672FF12FD37FEA744D6" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1870" box="[199,294,657,683]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphagidae" genus="Pagopedilum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis id="94D1EAB301546672FF12FD37FEA744D6" box="[199,294,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">P. brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="61A54D2201546672FD8BFD37FD7B44D6" baseAuthorityName="Saussure" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[606,762,657,683]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphagidae" genus="Pagopedilum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bradyanum">
<emphasis id="94D1EAB301546672FD8BFD37FD7B44D6" box="[606,762,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">P. bradyanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the former has a higher pronotum and mid abdominal segments dentate, while the latter has a lower pronotum and abdominal segments not dentate. Antennae of 
<taxonomicName id="61A54D2201546672FA5DFD13FF5B448E" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1870" class="Insecta" family="Pamphagidae" genus="Pagopedilum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis id="94D1EAB301546672FA5DFD13FF5B448E" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">P. brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are shorter than those of 
<taxonomicName id="61A54D2201546672FE22FD7FFD12448E" baseAuthorityName="Saussure" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[503,659,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphagidae" genus="Pagopedilum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bradyanum">
<emphasis id="94D1EAB301546672FE22FD7FFD12448E" box="[503,659,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">P. bradyanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A61A36A101546672FF12FD58FD8C456A" blockId="10.[151,1437,153,791]" box="[199,525,765,791]" pageId="10" pageNumber="39">
